    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Julia Moskin's article on cooking with cheap wine (''It Boils Down to This: Cheap Wine Works Fine,'' March 21) spoke of ''a California chardonnay so oaky it tasted as if it had been aged in a box of No. 2 pencils.'' This was witty but inaccurate. According to Henry Petroski's book ''The Pencil: A History of Design and Circumstance,'' the standard wood used in pencils is cedar, not oak. Ms. Moskin could surely taste the difference.</p>
        <p>John T. Durkin  Ardmore, Pa.</p>
      </block>
